Problem: 5.3-15. Three drugs are being tested for use as the treatment of a certain disease. Let $p_1, p_2$, and $p_3$ represent the probabilities of success for the respective drugs. As three patients come in, each is given one of the drugs in a random order. After $n=10$ "triples" and assuming independence, compute the probability that the maximum number of successes with one of the drugs exceeds eight if, in fact, $p_1=p_2=p_3=0.7$
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The problem requires finding the probability that the maximum number of successes for any one of the three drugs exceeds 8 after 10 triples, with each drug having a success probability of 0.7 per trial.

Each drug has 10 independent trials (since there are 10 triples, and each drug is administered once per triple). The number of successes for each drug follows a binomial distribution with parameters \(n = 10\) and \(p = 0.7\).

The probability that the maximum number of successes exceeds 8 is equivalent to the probability that at least one drug has more than 8 successes. This is calculated as:

\[
P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) > 8) = 1 - P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) \leq 8) = 1 - P(S_1 \leq 8, S_2 \leq 8, S_3 \leq 8)
\]

Due to independence and identical distribution:

\[
P(S_1 \leq 8, S_2 \leq 8, S_3 \leq 8) = [P(S_i \leq 8)]^3
\]

First, compute \(P(S_i \leq 8)\) for one drug:

\[
P(S_i \leq 8) = 1 - P(S_i = 9) - P(S_i = 10)
\]

\[
P(S_i = 9) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3)^1 = 10 \times (0.7)^9 \times 0.3
\]

\[
(0.7)^9 = 0.040353607
\]

\[
P(S_i = 9) = 10 \times 0.040353607 \times 0.3 = 0.121060821
\]

\[
P(S_i = 10) = (0.7)^{10} = 0.0282475249
\]

\[
P(S_i > 8) = P(S_i = 9) + P(S_i = 10) = 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459
\]

\[
P(S_i \leq 8) = 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541
\]

Now, compute \([P(S_i \leq 8)]^3\):

\[
(0.8506916541)^3 \approx 0.6156246
\]

Thus:

\[
P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) > 8) = 1 - 0.6156246 = 0.3843754
\]

Rounding to three significant figures, the result is 0.384.

Summary: The final answer is 0.384
